/r9k/ is an imageboard where there are no exact reposts.

1. If you attempt to post something unoriginal, it is not posted, and you are muted temporarily.
2. The time with which you are muted for doubles with each transgression.
3. Each mute time is 2^n in seconds where n is the number of times you have transgressed. So, your mute time doubles each time you fuck up.
4. Backlinks, eg >>1, are not viewed by the robot. So "lolwut" and ">>2 lolwut" are the same post, in the eyes of the robot.
5. Gibberish at the end of a post to force originality may result in mod intervention (no BLOX posts please).
6. Images are NOT included in the filter, only text.
7. Your mute count slowly decreases over time.
8. You cannot post a picture without text.
9. Unicode is blocked. Sorry, too many exploits (Cyrillic letters, etc).
10. Posts require a certain minimum amount of original content in order to be posted.
11. Post sane, real content, well thought out replies, and mutes are unlikely.
12. The original algorithm was designed by XKCD:
http://blag.xkcd.com/2008/01/14/robot9000-and-xkcd-signal-attacking-noise-in-chat/

>Do you view your waifu differently in any way now that they are your waifu, compared to when you first discovered them?
Yes. I went through various different "interpretations" of Shadow in my head, or assumptions about his personality that were far off.
I originally discovered Shadow sometime around on 4kids TV at ~6 years old, without playing any video games that featured him, so a notoriously shit dub was all I knew. I don't remember thinking anything at first, but I don't remember enough.
It grew into a steady dislike as I saw a few of his appearances in that dub. See, without any knowledge of him he initially comes across as some complete nigh-villainous asshole who's stronger than everyone else in the cast. I also was a HUGE diehard Knuckles x Rouge shipper, and came to view him as competition since Shadow and Rouge are allies and thus a decently popular ship among fans.
This changed when I started taking interest in what the games did and watched the cutscenes. And I can still vaguely remember the feeling of "oh, shoot" when the guy I had hated for a surface level assumption had actually been a good person who had killed himself for his own mistake.
What followed was him very quickly becoming my favorite character as I tried to learn more about him with the new knowledge that he wasn't a bad person and his past had been terrible.

...Leading me straight into a second misconception lol. Fan interpretations, noncanon media, soon enough I had this vision in my head that he was some angel good boy who dindu nuffin and any morally dark actions he took weren't his fault. I could explain more but this is already long. Basically though, that 2nd misconception that he was always a good boy was slapped out of me when I was shown proof he tries to kill people.
With every step I take towards knowing the truth of his heart, my love for him grows brighter.

>TL DR
Shadow is an awful jerk --> Shadow is a perfect angel --> Shadow is an angelic jerk

>>71957557
>If wise people existed, they would've figured out how to end scarcity, murder, war, etc.

This argument is retarded. No one can solve every problem that's facing society in their lifetimes by themselves, but through millennia of continued effort we've certainly come a long way from where we were just a couple thousands years ago. And one the main engines of that progress has undoubtedly been our increasingly profound knowledge about the world and ourselves: from learning to make fire, to simple agricultural techniques and eventually to modern technology, all of this steps where possible thanks to us understanding our environment a bit more every time. Sure, we may never be able to learn the complete truth about everything and achieve a full understanding of the universe, but there's no reason why we can't come close.

The same idea holds at an individual level. Obviously, these huge developments I've referenced before mean that experts have to specialize in increasing specific fields and can't be generalists like the old Greek philosophers. This, however, is not so much a limit of our individual capacity but rather a product of the fact that, since our understanding of certain areas has become so complex and deep, we need specialists committed to a single niche to be able to advance knowledge in a certain area. And yet outside of our professional development there's a huge margin for us to study other problems that interest us, even though we may never understand them as thoroughly as those who have dedicated their entire life to that field.

And the absolute best medium for doing that are books (and here I'm also including scientific journals and the like). It's true that you can get knowledge by other means, but no other medium offers the possibility of going into deep explanations as the long-form written word do. There's a limit to how much we can express via conversation, or in the 2000 character limit of a 4chan post, and that's why we have books.

A book is a printed website and a website is an uploaded book, with some differences in formatting and layout etc.

I like concise writing. If something is concise it doesn't automatically mean it's shallow. When you read through an entire book, and think about it for a while, you can probably distill the information you took away from it into one page. There's a lot of fluff in-between.

Another important issue is old vs. new. As you move forward in time, and read more modern works, you will notice that these are old ideas with way more bloat.
The more time passes, the more things bloat. Even this post is already too long.
Ancient writing is more concise, and therefore better. It simply conveys information and ideas. There's a lot of substance.
It's like the gauss curve. First, yellow fireball rise in sky. Then, lots of information about the fireball, it's called the sun, it's very hot, etc etc. Then the final phase, acceptance. Even with all this additional knowledge, yellow fireball still rise in sky.
The ancient Greeks were at a sweet spot in human history: language and thinking was just complex enough to explore all important ideas, and not yet bloated by carbs and corn.

posts.com:
its 245 AM

ive been in bed for almost 25 days now because of a bad motorcycle wreck. ive had a lot of time to think, although most of it has been sleeping. for some reason, it feels like death laughed at me.


ive had a lot of time to think about everything, but grandma has come to my mind quite a bit. even though its only been like its been 25 days. they kinda all just mesh together
into one mass eternity. it feels like ive been in bed for months. whenever grandma got sick it took years for her to pass away. she spent most of her time in a recliner
watching TV because she really couldnt do much else. i hardly remember any of the conversations i had with her in detail. which is a big shame because i wish i remembered
more, she was like my mom after all. although i vividly remember asking her about how she felt. this was during the time she could only respond with "yeah" and "no", because
the cerebral palsy had gotten so bad, she was basically running off of muscle memory. eventually it turned into just a "yeaa", so it had to be two yeas for no and one yea
for yes. either way, i remember while feeding her i asked her,"do you talk to yourself normally in your head like you used to?" and she said "yeah". then i remember asking
her, "do you feel like you are a prisoner of your own mind?" and she said yeah. i dont really remember much else than that, but i hope that she if anything, she felt like
someone had at least a comprehension of what she was going through. i wish she was still here, all of us. grandpa would be so happy, and she probably woulda whooped me and
sephs ass into shape and got us outta the house sooner! she was for sure the disciplinary one! maybe tomorrow, ill go pay her grave a visit. hopefully its not too cold.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
but i cant help but feel immense guilt for a lot of the things that i guess " i wish i coulda done ". dont get me wrong, i did my share, but it should have been more than that
i should have given grandma all the love and attention she needed to at least get better, to move around the house, to do whatever she needed to get better. i hate that i let it all
slip by. i was just trying to avoid it, partly because i was a teenager trying to get out and find the world, trying to discover all those things that kids do; however i realize now that
i was avoiding the pain of it all. even though i couldnt really feel it at the time. its all come back, delayed and in waves over years, being buried by new and more immediate problems and pains.
i cant imagine what it was like, to sit there for what must have felt like lifetimes, constantly getting soaked in your own shit and piss, having to take ABCDEF and G pills every day just so she
could not get constipated or so her eyes wouldnt dry up, or so she could fall asleep at night. having to rely on everyone to do everything for you, having two borderline useless grandchildren not
even helping your struggling husband who is unironically breaking himself trying to lift you around and take care of you, feed you, etc. i tried, i tried a lot. but i didnt care enough. i cared
more about running away from the problem, i cared more about the stuff i wanted to do. i didnt want to face the reality that my family is crumbling in front of me.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
i cant imagine the weight she felt on her shoulders. putting her family through hardship, although if i could go back id tell her its ok, we wouldn't be here if we didnt love her!. although i would always say the thing she
told me quite often. "you told me once, i wiped your ass when you were younger, and you're gonna wipe mine when im older. well look at us now!" and we'd all have a good laugh over it. i remember
taking her out for wheelchair rides, to much regret not so much after we moved. im sure feeling the sun on her skin was a great blessing for her. i could go on about woulda coulda wining bullshit.
im sure grandma doesnt want me to remember her as a feeble old lady that i had to take care of. the point is i REGRET not doing MORE, i regret not doing EVERYTHING i could to be there for her.
i didn't live by the idea that, if she died tomorrow, would i be able to say "I did everything i could do". im truly sorry for failing you grandma, im sorry you had to die and suffer alone in that
home because me and seph couldn't do it anymore. im sorry after time we started to visit less, im sorry that i didnt do everything in my power to save you, im sorry i didnt take you outta there.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
but this being said, to anyone reading this. if theres someone out there that needs your help, give it to them! be there for them! you might not have another chance to be there for them!
you could live in regret, brought down by shame and guilt of the past. if you love someone, show it! let them know you love them, let them know youre there for them. even if you dont have anyone
surely theres someone out there that deserves help, love, attention, or whatever you can give them, and while this is reality, and nothing is fair, maybe that person, or someone you were there for
will be there for you when you need them most.

either way, ive really had this stuff on my mind because ive been in bed basically helpless for what feels like forever, and ive had nothing but time to think. how i live right now,
my grandma would have found that a luxury. even though i can barely comprehend truly, it gave me a slight glimpse into what she had to endure for years and years on end, just to die alone around
some nurse that doesn't even care about you, being doped up on morphine and starved to death. Now, while this was all quite depressing, im hoping ill take this as a lesson to myself, and
fill myself with determination to do whatever i need, to be there for people that need me, and to stop wasting time, to stop taking shit for granted, to stop wasting away doing pointless tasks.
what we all have now is a freedom, most of us have able bodies and minds to do what we need to do, and we give up with the slightest downfall!? how would most of us ever take a true blow?
many of us probably couldnt. im not trying to say peoples problems are invalid, cus they aren't, we all have them. but i feel like many of us take simple things we have for granted too often.
what if you were to lose your arm? or become crippled? or deathly ill? then what, would you be satisfied with your life? your actions? thats something only you can answer yourself. i love you grandma.
